    load("../../data/week2/glasgowno2.RData")

We start by plotting the data, just like in the previous step.

    plot(no2, axes=FALSE, ylab=expression(NO[2]),xlim=c(1,9), col=2)          
    axis(2)
    axis(1, labels=c("31/01", "01/02", "02/02", "03/02", "04/02", "05/02", "06/02", "07/02", "08/02"), at=1:9)

Fitting and forecassting from an exponential smoothing model is however
much easier. We use the function `ets` from the package forecast. The
argument `model` lets us specify the type of model. The first letter
specifies the error type. The second letter denotes the trend type and
the third letter the type of sesonal term ("N" - exclude term, "A" -
additive term, "M" - multiplicative term, or "Z" - automatic selection).
We want everything to be chosen automatically, so we will use
`model="ZZZ"`.

    library(forecast)
    model <- ets(no2, model="ZZZ")
    summary(model)

    ## ETS(A,N,A) 
    ## 
    ## Call:

    forecast <- forecast(model, n.ahead=52)

We can now add the forecasts to the plot.

    plot(no2, axes=FALSE, ylab=expression(NO[2]),xlim=c(1,9), col=2)          
    axis(2)
    axis(1, labels=c("31/01", "01/02", "02/02", "03/02", "04/02", "05/02", "06/02", "07/02", "08/02"), at=1:9)
    newt <- length(no2)+1:48
    abline(v=1+140/24, lty=2)
    lines(1+newt/24, forecast$mean, col=4)

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
The predictions seem a little low and illustrate a problem with
exponential forecasting. The automatic algorithm selected *α* to be
almost 1, i.e. virtually only the last value is being used. Manually
forcing a lower value of *α* improved the predictions a lot.

    library(forecast)
    model <- ets(no2, model="ZZZ", alpha=0.15)
    summary(model)

    ## ETS(M,N,A) 
    ## 
    ## Call:
    ##  ets(y = no2, model = "ZZZ", alpha = 0.15) 
    ## 
    ##   Smoothing parameters:
    ##     alpha = 0.15 
    ##     gamma = 5e-04 
    ## 
    ##   Initial states:
    ##     l = 35.7225 
    ##     s = -8.6387 -1.7833 7.9828 14.4102 14.8472 9.397
    ##            19.0246 6.2869 -7.9352 -4.0478 0.058 5.2797 14.4216 7.9456 16.2921 24.465 18.4008 -1.3903 -18.2975 -27.1202 -25.334 -23.9238 -21.1224 -19.2183
    ## 
    ##   sigma:  0.3195
    ## 
    ##      AIC     AICc      BIC 
    ## 1482.443 1494.868 1558.926 
    ## 
    ## Training set error measures:
    ##                     ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
    ## Training set 0.1960527 14.63064 11.43502 -8.276476 26.10683 0.6747011
    ##                   ACF1
    ## Training set 0.7363037

    forecast <- forecast(model, n.ahead=52)
    plot(no2, axes=FALSE, ylab=expression(NO[2]),xlim=c(1,9), col=2)
